## Feature Request

Incorporate the parallel read functions from neuroh5.

inputs: gids, attribute names, filtering dictionary of form {value_name: boolean_function}

outputs: dict: {gid: {value_name: values}}

When using a `DjangoConnectionField` and performing a filter on the queryset in the resolve method, an empty queryset will result all the objects being returned.

For example

```python
import graphene
from graphene.contrib.django.fields import DjangoConnectionField
from graphene.contrib.django.types import DjangoNode

from .models import Category


class CategoryNode(DjangoNode):
    class Meta:
        model = Category


class Query(graphene.ObjectType):
    categories = DjangoConnectionField(
        CategoryNode,
        name=graphene.String(),
    )

    def resolve_categories(self, args, info):
        return Category.objects.filter(name__icontains=args['name'])
```

```graphql
query {
  hasMatch: categories(name: "food") {
    edges {
      node {
        name
      }
    }
  }
  noMatch: categories(name: "no matches asdf") {
    edges {
      node {
        name
      }
    }
  }
}
```

```js
{
  "data": {
    "hasMatch": {
      "edges": [
        [...just "food" categories returned]
      ]
    },
    "noMatch": {
      "edges": [
        [...all categories returned]
      ]
    }
  }
}
```

In this simple case. If the `name` arg returns a queryset with results, those results will be used. Otherwise, all categories will be returned.

This doesn't apply to `django-filters` based filtering, just these simple cases. However, if you're using these simple filters for something like security then this becomes a huge issue.

